  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison suspects that a letter he sent to Oliver Johnson may have been supressed. He praises Oliver Johnson&apos;s &quot;farewell address to the readers of the Standard.&quot; He feels that Oliver Johnson has the right to resent the charges Wendell Phillips made against him and the National Anti-Slavery Standard. Garrison feels that Oliver Johnson has &quot;nothing to regret, nothing to modify, nothing to recall, but much to be proud of.&quot; Garrison still has an address on the assassination of Lincoln to prepare and deliver in Providence.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Includes an envelope with the delivery address: Oliver Johnson, Esq., 90 East 12th Street, New York City, N.Y.</subfield>
